A MAN NAMED RONALD CLARK RECALLS HIS CHILDHOOD.
HE REMEMBERS GROWING UP AND THINKING THAT HIS FAMILY WAS WELL-OFF, BUT HIS PARENTS TOLD HIM THAT WASN'T TRUE.
THEN ONE DAY HIS DAD WAS HIRED AS A CUSTODIAN FOR THE WASHINGTON PARK LIBRARY.
AS THE CUSTODIAN, HIS DAD (AND HIS FAMILY) WERE ABLE TO LIVE ABOVE THE LIBRARY.
RONALD TALKS ABOUT HOW, COMPARED TO OTHER LIBRARIANS, HIS FATHER REALLY DID HIS JOB AND HE DID IT WELL.
HE WENT ABOVE AND BEYOND - EVEN POLISHING THE TOPS OF THE BOOKCASES.
RONALD NOTES THAT HE NEVER HAD FRIENDS OVER GROWING UP, AND THAT HE FELT THAT OTHERS THOUGHT IT WAS WEIRD HE LIVED THERE.
HOWEVER, HE SAID THAT THE BEST PART WAS THAT HE COULD HAVE THE WHOLE PLACE TO HIMSELF AT NIGHT.
HE LATER WENT ON TO BE THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE COLLEGE.
HE TALKS ABOUT SHOWING HIS DAD THE PLAQUE ON THE DOOR TO HIS OFFICE WHEN HE LATER BECAME A PROFESSOR AT A UNIVERSITY.
HE SAID HE COULD TELL HIS DAD WAS VERY PROUD OF HIM.
FINALLY, RONALD NOTES THAT HE DOESN'T KNOW HOW HIS LIFE WOULD BE IF HE HADN'T GROWN UP LIVING IN THE LIBRARY.
A MAN NAMED RONALD TALKS ABOUT GROWING UP IN NEW YORK CITY.
HE INITIALLY THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS WELL-OFF, BUT HIS PARENTS DIDN'T AGREE WITH HIM.
THEN HIS DAD GOT A JOB WORKING AS A CUSTODIAN IN A LIBRARY.
THE FAMILY MOVED IN TO THE WASHINGTON PARK LIBRARY, WHICH WAS ONE OF THE PERKS OF HIS DAD HAVING THE JOB.
RONALD REMEMBERS THAT HIS FATHER WAS A VERY HARD WORKER, EVEN GOING SO FAR AS TO WAX THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
HE SAID THAT HE DIDN'T HAVE FRIENDS OVER GROWING UP AND THAT SOME PEOPLE THOUGHT THAT HIS LIVING IN A LIBRARY WAS WEIRD.
HE EXPLAINS HOW HE LOVED READING, BUT HE HAD TO BE QUIET THROUGHOUT THE DAY.
HOWEVER, AT NIGHT HE HAD THE WHOLE BUILDING TO HIMSELF AND HE COULD READ AND STAY UP FOR HOURS.
HE LATER WENT ON TO GRADUATE COLLEGE, WHICH IS SOMETHING THAT NO ONE IN HIS FAMILY HAD DONE BEFORE.
HE BECAME A PROFESSOR AND GOT HIS OWN OFFICE WITH A PLAQUE OUTSIDE WITH HIS NAME, "PROFESSOR CLARK".
HE RECALLS SHOWING HIS FATHER, WHO WAS LARGELY QUIET ABOUT IT.
HOWEVER, RONALD KNOWS THAT HIS FATHER WAS PROUD OF HIM.
HE STATES HOW HE DOESN'T KNOW HOW HIS LIFE WOULD HAVE BEEN IF HE HADN'T GROWN UP IN THAT LIBRARY.
